Use `ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo` to load armature data before creating armatures:

```typescript
// Simple form — single ExportJson file
ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo('res/hero/hero.ExportJson');

// Extended form — with separate image and plist
ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo(
    'res/hero/hero.png',
    'res/hero/hero.plist',
    'res/hero/hero.ExportJson'
);
```

This must be called before `ccs.Armature.create()`. Typically done in scene initialization or a loading screen.

First load the armature data, then create and position the armature:

```typescript
// 1. Load data (once, e.g., in scene init)
ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo('res/hero/hero.ExportJson');

// 2. Create armature by name
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
```

You can also use the constructor:
```typescript
const armature = new ccs.Armature('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
```

`ccs.Armature` extends `cc.Node`, so all standard node methods (setPosition, setScale, setRotation, etc.) work on it.

Use the `animation` property of the armature, then call `play()`:

```typescript
ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo('res/hero/hero.ExportJson');
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);

// Play animation
armature.animation.play('run', -1, 1);
```

The `play` signature is:
```typescript
armature.animation.play(
    animationName: string,
    durationTo?: number,   // frames to blend (-1 = no blend)
    loop?: number          // -1 = forever, 0 = no loop, 1+ = count
): void
```

Common patterns:
```typescript
armature.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);   // loop forever, no blend
armature.animation.play('attack', 5, 0);   // play once, blend over 5 frames
armature.animation.play('walk', 8, -1);    // loop, blend transition in 8 frames
```

Use `setMovementEventCallFunc` on the armature's animation:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);

armature.animation.setMovementEventCallFunc((arm, movType, movId) => {
    if (movType === ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE) {
        cc.log('Animation complete:', movId);
    } else if (movType === ccs.MovementEventType.LOOP_COMPLETE) {
        cc.log('Loop iteration complete:', movId);
    } else if (movType === ccs.MovementEventType.START) {
        cc.log('Animation started:', movId);
    }
});

armature.animation.play('attack', -1, 0);
```

The callback receives:
- `arm: ccs.Armature` — the armature instance
- `movType: number` — one of `ccs.MovementEventType.START`, `COMPLETE`, or `LOOP_COMPLETE`
- `movId: string` — the name of the animation movement

Frame events are triggered by keyframes set in CocosStudio. Register a callback with `setFrameEventCallFunc`:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);

armature.animation.setFrameEventCallFunc((bone, eventName, origFrame, curFrame) => {
    if (eventName === 'footstep') {
        cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/sfx_step.mp3');
    } else if (eventName === 'spawn_projectile') {
        this.spawnProjectile(bone.getWorldPosition());
    }
});

armature.animation.play('run', -1, -1);
```

The callback receives:
- `bone: ccs.Bone` — the bone that triggered the event
- `eventName: string` — the event name defined in CocosStudio
- `origFrame: number` — the original frame index of the event
- `curFrame: number` — the current frame index during playback

This is useful for syncing sound effects, particle effects, or gameplay logic to specific animation frames.

```typescript
const anim = armature.animation;

// Total number of animations available
const count: number = anim.getMovementCount();

// Name of the currently playing animation
const currentId: string = anim.getCurrentMovementID();

// Get/set the raw animation data
const data: ccs.AnimationData = anim.getAnimationData();
anim.setAnimationData(data);

// Speed scale
const speed: number = anim.getSpeedScale();
```

Example — cycle through all animations:
```typescript
const anim = armature.animation;
const totalAnims = anim.getMovementCount();
let currentIndex = 0;

anim.setMovementEventCallFunc((arm, type, id) => {
    if (type === ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE) {
        currentIndex = (currentIndex + 1) % totalAnims;
        anim.playWithIndex(currentIndex, 5, 0);
    }
});

anim.playWithIndex(0, -1, 0);
```

Use `setSpeedScale` on the armature's animation controller:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('run', -1, -1);

// Normal speed
armature.animation.setSpeedScale(1.0);

// Double speed
armature.animation.setSpeedScale(2.0);

// Half speed (slow motion)
armature.animation.setSpeedScale(0.5);

// Read current speed
const currentSpeed: number = armature.animation.getSpeedScale();
```

`1.0` is normal speed. Values above 1.0 speed up the animation, values below 1.0 slow it down.

Use the bone access methods on the armature:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);

// Get a bone by name
const headBone: ccs.Bone = armature.getBone('head');

// Get bone at a screen coordinate (useful for hit testing)
const hitBone: ccs.Bone = armature.getBoneAtPoint(touchX, touchY);

// Get all bones as a dictionary
const allBones: object = armature.getBoneDic();

// Create a new bone
const newBone: ccs.Bone = armature.createBone('customBone');

// Add a bone under a parent
armature.addBone(newBone, 'body');

// Remove a bone (recursion=true removes children too)
armature.removeBone(newBone, true);

// Re-parent a bone
armature.changeBoneParent(headBone, 'neck');
```

Bone properties:
```typescript
const name: string = headBone.getName();
const worldPos: cc.Point = headBone.getWorldPosition();
headBone.setVisible(false);  // hide this bone
```

```typescript
ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo('res/hero/hero.ExportJson');
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('attack', -1, 0);

// Get the hand bone
const handBone: ccs.Bone = armature.getBone('hand_r');

// Get its world position (updates each frame with animation)
const worldPos: cc.Point = handBone.getWorldPosition();

// Attach a particle effect at the bone's position
const particle = new cc.ParticleSystem('res/fx/slash.plist');
particle.setPosition(worldPos);
this.addChild(particle);

// For continuous tracking, update in scheduleUpdate:
this.scheduleUpdate();
// In update:
update(dt: number): void {
    const pos = armature.getBone('hand_r').getWorldPosition();
    particle.setPosition(pos);
}
```

`getWorldPosition()` returns the bone's position in world coordinates, accounting for the armature's position, scale, and current animation pose.

Use `playWithNames` to play a sequence of animations in order:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);

// Play 'jump', 'flip', 'land' in sequence, blending over 5 frames, no loop
armature.animation.playWithNames(['jump', 'flip', 'land'], 5, false);

// Play a looping sequence
armature.animation.playWithNames(['walk', 'idle'], 8, true);
```

Signature:
```typescript
armature.animation.playWithNames(
    names: string[],
    durationTo?: number,  // blend frames between transitions
    loop?: boolean        // loop the entire sequence
): void
```

The equivalent index-based version:
```typescript
armature.animation.playWithIndexes([0, 2, 1], 5, false);
```

Use the `durationTo` parameter in the `play` method to smoothly blend from the current animation to a new one:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);

// Start with idle (no blend needed for first animation)
armature.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);

// Later, blend to walk over 8 frames
armature.animation.play('walk', 8, -1);

// Blend to run over 5 frames
armature.animation.play('run', 5, -1);
```

The `durationTo` parameter specifies how many frames the blend transition takes:
- `-1` = no blending, immediate switch
- `0` = instant switch (same as -1)
- `5-10` = smooth blend, good for walk/run transitions
- Higher values = slower, smoother transitions

This creates natural-looking transitions between animation states, similar to animation blend trees in 3D engines.

These methods let you jump to a specific frame:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('attack', -1, 0);

// Jump to frame 10 and continue playing from there
armature.animation.gotoAndPlay(10);

// Jump to frame 0 and pause (freeze at that pose)
armature.animation.gotoAndPause(0);

// Later, resume playback
armature.animation.resume();
```

Use cases:
- **`gotoAndPlay`**: Skip to a specific part of an animation, useful for syncing with game events
- **`gotoAndPause`**: Freeze at a specific pose, useful for character select screens, previews, or manual frame-by-frame control

```typescript
// Manual frame scrubbing (e.g., tied to a slider)
function setAnimationFrame(armature: ccs.Armature, frame: number): void {
    armature.animation.gotoAndPause(frame);
}
```

Use `ccs.actionManager` to load timeline animations from `.csb` files:

```typescript
// Load the timeline action from a .csb file
const timeline = ccs.actionManager.loadAnimationActionWithFile('res/ui/dialog.csb');

// Run the action on a node
const dialogNode = new cc.Node();
this.addChild(dialogNode);
dialogNode.runAction(timeline);

// Play from frame 0, looping
timeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(0, true);

// Play from frame 0, no loop
timeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(0, false);

// Pause at a specific frame
timeline.gotoFrameAndPause(0);
```

The `ccs.ActionTimeline` API:
```typescript
timeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(frame: number, loop: boolean): void
timeline.gotoFrameAndPause(frame: number): void
timeline.setCurrentFrame(frame: number): void
timeline.getCurrentFrame(): number
timeline.getStartFrame(): number
timeline.getEndFrame(): number
timeline.setTimeSpeed(speed: number): void
timeline.getTimeSpeed(): number
```

`ccs.Armature` and `ccs.ActionTimeline` are two different animation systems in CocosStudio:

**ccs.Armature (Skeletal Animation)**
- Uses bones and skeletal deformation
- Best for character animations (walk, run, attack)
- Animations are named movements (e.g., 'idle', 'run')
- Controlled via `armature.animation.play('name')`
- Supports bone manipulation, frame events, movement events
- Exports as `.ExportJson` files

**ccs.ActionTimeline (Timeline Animation)**
- Uses keyframe-based property animation
- Best for UI animations, scene transitions, simple node animations
- Frame-based control (gotoFrame, play range)
- Controlled via `timeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(frame, loop)`
- Exports as `.csb` files
- Runs as a `cc.Action` on any `cc.Node`

```typescript
// Armature approach (character)
ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo('res/hero.ExportJson');
const hero = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
hero.animation.play('run', -1, -1);

// Timeline approach (UI)
const timeline = ccs.actionManager.loadAnimationActionWithFile('res/ui/popup.csb');
popupNode.runAction(timeline);
timeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(0, false);
```

Use Armature for game characters, ActionTimeline for UI and simple animations.

Use `setColliderFilter` to configure collision filtering for the armature:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
this.addChild(armature);

// Set a collider filter on the entire armature
armature.setColliderFilter(filter);
```

You can also access individual bone colliders:
```typescript
const bone = armature.getBone('body');
const detector: ccs.ColliderDetector = bone.getColliderDetector();
```

The `ccs.ColliderDetector` from a bone provides collision detection data that was set up in CocosStudio's collision editor. This is useful for per-bone hit detection in fighting games or action games where different body parts have different hitboxes.

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);

// Register touch listener
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch): boolean => {
        const loc = touch.getLocation();
        const bone = armature.getBoneAtPoint(loc.x, loc.y);

        if (bone) {
            cc.log('Tapped bone:', bone.getName());
            // Different responses based on which bone was hit
            const boneName = bone.getName();
            if (boneName === 'head') {
                this.onHeadshot();
            } else if (boneName === 'body') {
                this.onBodyHit();
            }
        } else {
            cc.log('Missed the armature');
        }
        return true;
    }
}, this);
```

`getBoneAtPoint(x, y)` returns the topmost bone at the given world coordinates, or `null` if no bone is at that point. This enables precise per-bone hit testing.

Use `getBoundingBox()` which recalculates from all bones each call:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);

// Get bounding box
const box: cc.Rect = armature.getBoundingBox();
cc.log('x:', box.x, 'y:', box.y, 'w:', box.width, 'h:', box.height);

// Use for broad-phase collision detection
function checkCollision(armA: ccs.Armature, armB: ccs.Armature): boolean {
    const boxA = armA.getBoundingBox();
    const boxB = armB.getBoundingBox();
    return cc.rectOverlapsRect(boxA, boxB);
}
```

Note: `getBoundingBox()` recalculates from all bones on every call, so it reflects the current animation pose. This can be expensive if called frequently — cache the result per frame if needed.

Use `setBlendFunc` with either a `cc.BlendFunc` object or two blend constants:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('ghost');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('float', -1, -1);

// Additive blending for glowing/ghost effect
armature.setBlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE);

// Read current blend
const blend: cc.BlendFunc = armature.getBlendFunc();

// Reset to normal alpha blending
armature.setBlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA);
```

Overloads:
```typescript
armature.setBlendFunc(blendFunc: cc.BlendFunc): void
armature.setBlendFunc(src: cc.BlenderConst, dst: cc.BlenderConst): void
```

Common use cases: ghost/spirit characters (additive blend), shadow overlays (multiply blend).

```typescript
const enum CharState {
    IDLE = 'idle',
    WALK = 'walk',
    RUN = 'run',
    ATTACK = 'attack',
    HURT = 'hurt'
}

class CharacterController extends cc.Node {
    private _armature: ccs.Armature;
    private _state: CharState = CharState.IDLE;
    private _facingRight: boolean = true;

    constructor(armatureName: string, exportJson: string) {
        super();
        ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo(exportJson);
        this._armature = ccs.Armature.create(armatureName);
        this.addChild(this._armature);
        this.setupAnimEvents();
        this.setState(CharState.IDLE);
    }

    private setupAnimEvents(): void {
        this._armature.animation.setMovementEventCallFunc((arm, type, id) => {
            if (type === ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE) {
                if (id === CharState.ATTACK || id === CharState.HURT) {
                    this.setState(CharState.IDLE);
                }
            }
        });

        this._armature.animation.setFrameEventCallFunc((bone, eventName) => {
            if (eventName === 'attack_hit') {
                this.onAttackHit();
            }
        });
    }

    setState(state: CharState): void {
        if (this._state === state) return;
        if (this._state === CharState.ATTACK && state !== CharState.HURT) return;

        this._state = state;
        const loop = (state === CharState.IDLE || state === CharState.WALK || state === CharState.RUN) ? -1 : 0;
        this._armature.animation.play(state, 5, loop);
    }

    setFacing(right: boolean): void {
        if (this._facingRight === right) return;
        this._facingRight = right;
        this._armature.setScaleX(right ? 1 : -1);
    }

    attack(): void {
        this.setState(CharState.ATTACK);
    }

    private onAttackHit(): void {
        const handPos = this._armature.getBone('hand_r').getWorldPosition();
        cc.log('Attack hit at:', handPos.x, handPos.y);
    }
}

// Usage:
const hero = new CharacterController('hero', 'res/hero/hero.ExportJson');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setState(CharState.WALK);
hero.setFacing(false); // face left
```

```typescript
function loadArmatureSet(
    configs: Array<{ name: string; file: string }>
): void {
    for (const cfg of configs) {
        ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo(cfg.file);
    }
}

function playSyncedAnimation(
    armatures: ccs.Armature[],
    animName: string,
    speed: number
): void {
    for (const arm of armatures) {
        arm.animation.play(animName, -1, -1);
        arm.animation.setSpeedScale(speed);
        arm.animation.gotoAndPlay(0);
    }
}

// Usage:
loadArmatureSet([
    { name: 'dancer1', file: 'res/dancer1/dancer1.ExportJson' },
    { name: 'dancer2', file: 'res/dancer2/dancer2.ExportJson' },
    { name: 'dancer3', file: 'res/dancer3/dancer3.ExportJson' }
]);

const dancers: ccs.Armature[] = [];
const names = ['dancer1', 'dancer2', 'dancer3'];
const positions = [cc.p(120, 160), cc.p(240, 160), cc.p(360, 160)];

for (let i = 0; i < names.length; i++) {
    const arm = ccs.Armature.create(names[i]);
    arm.setPosition(positions[i]);
    this.addChild(arm);
    dancers.push(arm);
}

// All dancers perform 'dance' at the same speed, starting from frame 0
playSyncedAnimation(dancers, 'dance', 1.0);
```

```typescript
class GameScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _hero: ccs.Armature;
    private _uiTimeline: ccs.ActionTimeline;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this.initUI();
        this.initCharacter();
    }

    private initUI(): void {
        // Load CocosStudio UI with timeline animation
        const uiNode = new cc.Node();
        this.addChild(uiNode, 10);

        this._uiTimeline = ccs.actionManager.loadAnimationActionWithFile('res/ui/hud.csb');
        uiNode.runAction(this._uiTimeline);
        this._uiTimeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(0, true);
        this._uiTimeline.setTimeSpeed(1.0);
    }

    private initCharacter(): void {
        // Load armature character
        ccs.armatureDataManager.addArmatureFileInfo('res/hero/hero.ExportJson');
        this._hero = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
        this._hero.setPosition(240, 100);
        this.addChild(this._hero, 5);
        this._hero.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);

        // Sync frame events with UI
        this._hero.animation.setFrameEventCallFunc((bone, eventName) => {
            if (eventName === 'level_up') {
                this.playUIEffect();
            }
        });
    }

    private playUIEffect(): void {
        // Restart the UI timeline from frame 0
        this._uiTimeline.gotoFrameAndPlay(0, false);
    }
}
```

